  "prompt": "My friend block a person on what's app how could I know really he is blocked?",
  "response": "Okay, it's tricky to know for sure if someone has blocked you on WhatsApp because WhatsApp doesn't explicitly tell you. However, there are a few clues you can look for, but keep in mind that *none of them are definitive on their own*.  It's best to consider them together:\n\n*   **No longer see their profile picture:** If you can no longer see their profile picture, where you used to, this *could* indicate a block. However, they might have also simply removed their profile picture.\n\n*   **Single tick on messages:** When you send a message to someone who hasn't blocked you, you'll usually see one grey tick (message sent), then two grey ticks (message delivered), and then two blue ticks (message read). If your messages only ever show one grey tick, it means the message was sent from your end, but never delivered to their phone. This *could* mean you've been blocked, or it could mean they have no internet connection or have changed their number.\n\n*   **Can't see their \"last seen\" or \"online\" status:**  If you used to be able to see their \"last seen\" or \"online\" status under their name at the top of the chat, and now you can't, it *might* be a sign. However, they may have disabled this feature in their privacy settings.\n\n*   **WhatsApp call doesn't go through:** If you try to call them on WhatsApp and the call doesn't go through (it rings and rings without connecting, or goes straight to silence), it *could* be a sign. However, it could also mean they have poor internet or are simply not answering.\n\n*   **Cannot add them to a WhatsApp group:** This is a STRONGER indicator. If you try to create a new WhatsApp group and add them to it, and you get a message saying you're not authorized to add them, or an error message, it's a very strong indication that they have blocked you. This is probably the most reliable test.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Privacy Settings:** Many of these indicators can also be caused by the other person's privacy settings. They may have chosen to hide their profile picture, \"last seen\" status, or read receipts from everyone, or from people who aren't in their contacts.\n*   **Changing Phone/Number:** They may have changed their phone number and simply haven't updated it on WhatsApp.\n*   **Technical Issues:** Occasional glitches with WhatsApp can also cause some of these symptoms.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nThe *most reliable* way to get an indication is trying to add them to a group and if you can't then they have probably blocked you.\n",
